"""Generate card evaluation training data - Batch 2 (append). More playability assessments and comparisons."""
import json
import os

pairs = [
    # === MORE "IS THIS LEGACY PLAYABLE?" ===
    # Playable cards
    {"instruction": "Is Swords to Plowshares Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, it is the best creature removal spell ever printed. For just W at instant speed, it exiles a creature permanently. Exile is better than destroy (no graveyard recursion, handles indestructible). The life gain for the opponent is a real cost against combo where every point matters, but against creature decks it is negligible. Swords is in 21% of Legacy decks and is an automatic 4-of in any white deck."},
    {"instruction": "Is Chalice of the Void Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, it is one of the most format-defining cards. On turn 1 from Ancient Tomb, Chalice on 1 counters Brainstorm, Ponder, Swords to Plowshares, Lightning Bolt, Thoughtseize, Daze, and most of Legacy's best spells. It is the backbone of every prison/stompy strategy (Eldrazi, Red Stompy, Affinity). At 33% of decks running Ancient Tomb and many running Chalice, it is a format pillar."},
    {"instruction": "Is Uro, Titan of Nature's Wrath Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, though less dominant than it once was. Uro provides 3 life, draws a card, and ramps for 1UG on cast, then escapes from the graveyard as a 6/6 for the same effects repeatedly. In grindy control mirrors, Uro is nearly unbeatable card advantage. It sees play in Bant and 4-color control builds. The 3-mana initial cost and graveyard dependence are real drawbacks in a format with Surgical Extraction and Leyline of the Void."},
    {"instruction": "Is Thoughtseize Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, it is the best targeted hand disruption spell. For B and 2 life, you see the opponent's entire hand and take any nonland card. It is in 43% of Legacy decks. Thoughtseize is proactive disruption that works against every strategy: take combo pieces, take removal, take countermagic. The 2 life cost is minimal in a format where games are often decided by card quality rather than life totals. Automatic 4-of in any black tempo or combo deck."},
    {"instruction": "Is Monastery Mentor Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, in the right shell. Mentor creates a 1/1 Monk token with prowess for every noncreature spell you cast. In a cantrip-heavy deck, Mentor can create 3-5 tokens in a single turn, each of which gets prowess bonuses. It sees play in UW Control and Jeskai builds as a win condition that ends games in 2-3 turns. The 3-mana cost is high for Legacy, but the explosive potential justifies it."},
    {"instruction": "Is Snapcaster Mage Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Marginally. Snapcaster Mage was excellent in Legacy for years, but the format has moved away from it. At 1U for a 2/1 flash that gives a spell flashback, the rate is good. However, Orcish Bowmasters kills it on sight while generating value, and the 2-mana cost competes with more impactful plays. It still sees fringe play in control decks but is no longer a staple. It was better when the format was slower."},
    {"instruction": "Is Goblin Guide Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Only in Burn. Goblin Guide is a 2/2 haste for R, which is an aggressive rate, but the card reveal drawback is significant and the body is fragile. In Burn, you do not care about card advantage - you want to deal maximum damage before the opponent stabilizes. Goblin Guide represents 4-6 damage over 2-3 turns. Outside of Burn, it is too small and provides too much information to the opponent."},
    {"instruction": "Is Jace, the Mind Sculptor Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, though less dominant than in previous eras. Jace costs 2UU and provides: +2 to control opponent's draws, 0 to Brainstorm every turn, -1 to bounce a creature, and -12 to win the game. In control decks, Jace is one of the best win conditions because it provides card advantage every turn while threatening an ultimate. At 4 mana, it is too slow for tempo but perfect for control. It competes with faster card advantage like Up the Beanstalk."},
    # Not playable
    {"instruction": "Is Counterspell Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Barely, and mostly no. Counterspell costs UU to counter any spell, which seems great, but Legacy has Force of Will (free), Daze (free), Force of Negation (free on opponent's turn), and Flusterstorm (U for storm). Paying 2 mana to counter a spell is too slow when your opponent's spells cost 0-1 mana. The double-blue requirement is also restrictive. Counterspell sees occasional play in UW Control but has been largely replaced by more efficient alternatives."},
    {"instruction": "Is Tarmogoyf Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Barely, and declining. Tarmogoyf was Legacy's premier threat for a decade, but Barrowgoyf has mostly replaced it. Both grow based on card types in graveyards, but Barrowgoyf does not count the opponent's graveyard (which matters with Leyline of the Void) and has a more relevant creature type. More importantly, Murktide Regent is simply better: it flies, dodges Bolt, and is often larger. Goyf at 1G for a 4/5 is still powerful, but the format has outgrown it."},
    {"instruction": "Is Mana Leak Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "No. Mana Leak costs 1U and counters unless the opponent pays 3. In Legacy, this is worse than Daze (free), Force of Will (free), Spell Pierce (U, pay 2), and Flusterstorm (U, uncounterable vs instants/sorceries). By turn 3-4, opponents always have 3 mana to pay. Mana Leak is a Modern card that does not meet Legacy's efficiency standards. Every slot spent on Mana Leak would be better spent on a free or 1-mana counter."},
    {"instruction": "Is Doom Blade Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "No. Doom Blade costs 1B and destroys a nonblack creature. In Legacy, this fails on multiple levels: it costs 2 mana (too expensive for removal), it does not exile (important against recursion), it misses black creatures (Orcish Bowmasters, the most played creature, is black), and it destroys rather than exiling (Swords to Plowshares does both for W). Fatal Push at B is strictly better in almost every case. Snuff Out at 4 life is free. Legacy demands extreme mana efficiency from removal."},
    {"instruction": "Is Opt Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "No, or very rarely. Opt costs U to scry 1 then draw 1, seeing only 2 cards. Brainstorm (U, draw 3 put back 2 with shuffle) and Ponder (U, look at 3 with shuffle option) both see more cards for the same cost. Even Preordain (U, scry 2 draw 1) is better since it sees 3 cards. The only case for Opt is if you already play 4 Brainstorm + 4 Ponder and need a 9th cantrip, but even then Consider or Preordain are usually preferred."},
    {"instruction": "Is Ragavan, Nimble Pilferer Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "It WAS Legacy-playable and was in fact banned for being too good. Ragavan was a 1-mana 2/1 with dash that created a Treasure token and exiled the top card of the opponent's library (castable) on combat damage. A turn-1 Ragavan that connected generated mana AND card advantage, snowballing games immediately. It was in every UR/URx deck at high percentages. It was banned because a 1-drop should not generate that much advantage with no deckbuilding cost."},
    {"instruction": "Is Lightning Helix Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "No. Lightning Helix costs RW for 3 damage and 3 life. In Legacy, Lightning Bolt costs R for 3 damage. The extra W and 3 life do not justify an additional color requirement. Legacy removal needs to be as mana-efficient as possible. Helix would be fine in Standard but fails the Legacy test: is it better than the cheapest available alternative? Against Bolt, it is not. The life gain is negligible in a format where games are decided by card quality."},
    {"instruction": "Is Thoughtcast Legacy-playable?", "input": "", "output": "Yes, in artifact-heavy decks. Thoughtcast has affinity for artifacts, often costing U to draw 2 cards. In 8-Cast, Affinity Stompy, and Blue Artifacts decks, Thoughtcast is a 1-mana draw-2, which is absurdly efficient. It is unplayable outside dedicated artifact decks since without 4+ artifacts in play, it costs too much. In the right shell, it is one of the best card advantage spells in Legacy."},

    # === MORE CARD COMPARISONS ===
    {"instruction": "Toxic Deluge vs Terminus: which board wipe is better?", "input": "", "output": "Depends on the deck. Terminus (miracle W, regular 4WW) puts all creatures on the bottom of libraries - dodges indestructible and prevents graveyard triggers. Best in decks with cantrips that can set up the miracle. Toxic Deluge (1BB, pay X life for -X/-X) costs life but kills at instant-speed priority, bypasses indestructible, and scales precisely. Best in black decks that need a flexible sweeper. Terminus is better against True-Name Nemesis (protection does not stop non-targeting). Deluge is better against haste creatures and when you need a sweeper NOW."},
    {"instruction": "Surgical Extraction vs Extirpate: what is the difference?", "input": "", "output": "Surgical Extraction costs 2 life (Phyrexian mana) to exile all copies of a card from opponent's hand, graveyard, and library. Extirpate costs B and has split second (cannot be responded to except by mana abilities). In Legacy, Surgical is far more played because: 1) It costs 0 mana (pay life), allowing use while tapped out. 2) Split second from Extirpate is rarely relevant since the effect is instant-speed anyway. 3) Not needing B lets non-black decks play Surgical. Extirpate's one advantage: it stops Brainstorm in response (split second prevents casting)."},
    {"instruction": "Force of Vigor vs Nature's Claim: which artifact/enchantment removal is better?", "input": "", "output": "Force of Vigor costs 2GG or pitches a green card for free to destroy up to two artifacts and/or enchantments. Nature's Claim costs G to destroy one artifact or enchantment but gains the opponent 4 life. Force of Vigor is better in most Legacy contexts: it is free (critical against Chalice on 1 which prevents casting Claim), it destroys TWO targets (crucial against decks with multiple problematic artifacts), and Legacy games rarely care about 4 life. Claim is better when mana is plentiful and you only need to hit one target, or when the 4 life matters against Burn."},
    {"instruction": "Leyline of the Void vs Rest in Peace: which graveyard hate is better?", "input": "", "output": "Both exile cards that would go to the graveyard. Leyline starts in play for free if in your opening hand. Rest in Peace costs 1W and also exiles all cards currently in graveyards when it enters. Leyline is better in non-white decks (any deck can play it), against turn-1 combos (it is already in play), and when you use your own graveyard (it only affects opponents). Rest in Peace is better in white decks (castable if not in opener), when you need to clear existing graveyards, and combined with Helm of Obedience (combo). Most Legacy decks prefer Leyline due to the free start."},
    {"instruction": "Endurance vs Leyline of the Void: which graveyard hate is better?", "input": "", "output": "Different purposes. Leyline is a hard lock: cards never reach the graveyard at all. It completely shuts down Dredge, Reanimator, and Oops. Endurance is a one-shot effect: flash in, shuffle a graveyard into library. It delays graveyard strategies one turn but does not prevent them from rebuilding. Endurance's advantages: it is a 3/4 body with reach (relevant blocker), it works with Green Sun's Zenith, and it does not hurt your own graveyard. Leyline wins the graveyard matchup harder; Endurance is more flexible overall."},
    {"instruction": "Dark Confidant vs Sylvan Library: which card advantage engine is better?", "input": "", "output": "In the current format, Sylvan Library is significantly better. Dark Confidant is a 2/1 for 1B that draws an extra card per turn at the cost of life equal to its mana value. Orcish Bowmasters kills Confidant immediately while generating value, making it a liability. Sylvan Library costs 1G as an enchantment (harder to remove), lets you look at 3 cards per draw step, and choose to keep extras for 4 life each. Library provides better card selection without being vulnerable to creature removal."},
    {"instruction": "Delver of Secrets vs Dragon's Rage Channeler: which 1-drop threat is better?", "input": "", "output": "In the current format, Delver of Secrets is generally better. Delver flips into a 3/2 flyer which dodges ground blockers and attacks through board stalls. Dragon's Rage Channeler is a 1/1 that surveys (look at top, may put in graveyard) and becomes a 3/3 with flying at delirium (4 card types in graveyard). DRC was dominant alongside Ragavan, but post-Ragavan ban and with Orcish Bowmasters punishing 1-toughness creatures, DRC's 1/1 body is a liability. Delver's 0/1 back side survives Bowmasters' 1-damage ping before flipping."},
    {"instruction": "Wasteland vs Strip Mine: why is Strip Mine banned?", "input": "", "output": "Strip Mine destroys any land (including basics) with no mana cost beyond tapping and sacrificing itself. Wasteland only destroys nonbasic lands. This seemingly small difference is enormous: Strip Mine lets you keep an opponent permanently off mana by recurring it (with Life from the Loam or Crucible of Worlds), targeting their basics after they fetch them. Wasteland at least lets opponents fetch basic lands to play around it. Strip Mine would make Lands and any deck with recursion able to achieve a complete mana lock, which is considered too oppressive for Legacy."},
    {"instruction": "Show and Tell vs Natural Order: which cheat effect is better?", "input": "", "output": "Different strengths. Show and Tell (2U) puts any permanent from hand into play - your Emrakul, Omniscience, or Sneak Attack. Weakness: opponent also puts something in play. Natural Order (2GG) sacrifices a green creature to tutor any green creature directly into play. Weakness: needs a creature to sacrifice and only finds green creatures. Show and Tell is better for putting non-creature/non-green permanents into play and does not require a board. Natural Order is better when you want a specific creature (Craterhoof Behemoth) and already have a sacrifice-worthy creature (any elf)."},
    {"instruction": "Brazen Borrower vs Vendilion Clique: which 3-mana flash flyer is better?", "input": "", "output": "Context-dependent. Brazen Borrower bounces any nonland permanent as an adventure (Petty Theft, 1U instant), then can be cast as a 3/1 flash flyer for 1UU. Vendilion Clique is a 3/1 flash flyer for 1UU that looks at an opponent's hand and can exchange one card for a random draw. Borrower is better for board interaction (bouncing resolved threats) and against decks with few cards in hand. Clique is better for information and surgical disruption against combo (strip a key piece). In Dimir Tempo, Clique's information synergizes better with Thoughtseize."},
]

outpath = os.path.join(os.path.dirname(__file__), "..", "data", "training", "card_evaluation.jsonl")
with open(outpath, "a", encoding="utf-8") as f:
    for pair in pairs:
        f.write(json.dumps(pair, ensure_ascii=False) + "\n")

print(f"Appended {len(pairs)} pairs to {outpath}")
